
Shadow DOM

shadow DOM refers to a feature of web browsers that allows developers to create separte the DOM tree,
called a shadow tree, that is attached to a specific element and is hidden from the main document.


Shadow DOM is a feature of web browers that allows for scoping of CSS and javascript within a specific element.


Examples:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Shadow DOM Example</title>
    <style>
        /* Styles for the main document */
        h1 {
            color: red;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>This is a heading outside of Shadow DOM</h1>

<!-- A custom element with a shadow DOM -->
<custom-element></custom-element>

<script>
    // Define a custom element
    class CustomElement extends HTMLElement {
        constructor() {
            super();

            // Attach a shadow DOM to the element
            const shadow = this.attachShadow({ mode: 'open' });

            // Create content inside the shadow DOM
            const shadowHeading = document.createElement('h1');
            shadowHeading.textContent = 'This is inside Shadow DOM';

            // Apply scoped styles to shadow DOM
            const style = document.createElement('style');
            style.textContent = `
                h1 {
                    color: blue;
                }
            `;

            // Append the heading and style to the shadow root
            shadow.appendChild(style);
            shadow.appendChild(shadowHeading);
        }
    }

    // Register the custom element
    customElements.define('custom-element', CustomElement);
</script>

</body>
</html>
